er into a non-technical overview of its ecology. Strayer describes the geography and geology of the Hudson and its basin, the properties of water and its movements in the river, water chemistry, and the river’s plants and animals. He then takes a more detailed look at the Hudson’s ecosystems and each of its major habitats. Strayer also discusses important management challenges facing the river today, including pollution, habitat destruction, overfishing, invasive species, and ecological restoration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnvironmental protectionzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aEstuarine healthzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aHuman ecologyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNatural historyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aRestoration ecologyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aStream ecologyzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 0aWaterxPollutionzHudson River (N.Y. and N.J.). 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican culture.  aamerican history.  aconservation.  aearth sciences.  aecological restoration.  aecologists.  aecology.  aenvironmental impact.  afishermen.  aguidebook.  ahabitat destruction.  ahabitat loss.  ahudson river.  ainvasive species.  anew york.  aoverfishing.  aplants and animals.  ariver ecology.  ariver ecosystems.  ariver geography.  ariver geology.  ariver management.  ariver plants.  ariver pollution.  ariver scientists.  ascientists.  aunited states.  awater chemistry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026961340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095239340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document